text:
I know this is late, but I am one of those weird people that gets picky about water. I actually can barely stand "city water", as I call it. It's just the type of water most homes get, usually going through a treatment process and gets the fluoride or whatever they add to the water. I've gotten so used to simple well water (tastes about the same as the kind you get in a plastic water bottle) that just the teeniest change in the metals and/or chemicals is stupidly obvious to me. I've gotten myself to stop being a picky lil bish, but water in a town, suburbia, city, etc will always be second choice to a plastic bottle of water.

Honestly the water I'm used to could have something in it that's bad for me, but I'll never know.

text:
Also Ambidextrous just means you can use both hands in some form of regularity. A lot of people who are can't necessarily do every activity with both hands, but they often switch what activity they use which hands for in ways that don't make a lot of sense. Like if they write right handed, but bat lefty. They are activities that should use the same hand as they are technically doing the same kind of activity with both. An Ambidextrous person would use 1 hand for 1 and the other for the other. 

So what it truly means is Ambidextrous don't just use both hands as they want. They have to use both hands as much as possible to make up for not really specializing in one. It's a lot more complicated than it seems, and most people only have a very basic and inaccurate understanding to what it is. It makes playing pc games harder without a 17 or higher button mouse because I can't just use every keyboard button on my left hand for everything like a lot of pc gamers can. I have to split the actions between both my hands more evenly because it's just how my hands work. 

Though there are activities I can do with both hands almost as well. Writing isn't really one of them. Mainly because I'm really good at drawing and so I developed my right hand a lot for it. I can still write with both hands with some success but I don't practice with my left at all for that activity. However in martial arts I can do something most people can't. Most of the time you switch from your main side to a southpaw ish side to match who you would be fighting. However I don't change into the Southpaw part really. I can fight left handed and right handed at the same time and switch between them. Most people fight predominantly one sided and can't switch to a full variation of the opposing side. 

In hockey I could hold my stick right and left handed, but was predominantly left sided most of the time. However, if you played hockey you would know there are weird situations you can get into for being predominantly one side. So switching stick sides can help defend the puck/ball better. Poke checks are your worst enemy in hockey because it's so easy to successfully do, but someone like me is almost unaffected by them entirely. 

I can't swim above water at all because it's a technique that guides with 1 hand, but I can underwater swim faster than most people. I'm extremely fast underwater and probably faster than people who do swim above water. Under water swimming requires rotated full use of both hands and feet so it is a lot easier for me to do. 

Those are examples I can think of for now. I can probably explain a difference for every activity I've ever done due to it. It's like an entirely different mindset Ambidextrous people have that people of only 1 can't really fathom. It's not really using left or right, but a third option entirely different than them.

I just typed this as it might interest someone. I personally have fun with information dumps like this so I don't really understand when people misunderstand my intent with such posts. xD
